Title: President
Description:
Ron Arnason, President

Ron Arnason achieved a Bachelor of Science degree in Agriculture in 1976 and a Masters of Business Administration degree in 1980, both from the University of Manitoba.  He has over 30 years experience as a manager and owner in the feed and livestock industry.  Ron was a partner and a senior manager of the Landmark Feeds Group and became president of Landmark Feeds Inc. in 1997.  After the company was acquired by Maple Leaf Foods, Ron served on the Maple Leaf Foods Executive Council.  Ron assumed the additional role of President of Elite Swine Inc. before retiring from Maple Leaf Foods in 2005.  Ron served as a Director of the Animal Nutrition Association of Canada for several years, finally serving as its Chairman in 2001-02.

Title: Exploration Manager
Description:
Andrew Bullock

Mr. Bullock has been involved for 25 years in successful exploration, development, and acquisition ventures throughout Western Canada and the Canadian frontiers. He brings to the company a working knowledge of a wide repertoire of play types in a variety of geological settings. He graduated from McMaster University in 1981 with a Bachelor of Science Honors Degree in Geology, and is a member of APEGGA. Most recently (2001-2004) Mr. Bullock was the G&G Supervisor responsible for directing the exploration and development strategy in ConocoPhillips' West Central, Alberta , region. Targets were met every year primarily as a result of the drilling over 150 wells during his tenure, targeting more than 10 stratigraphic horizons, ranging from the Devonian Leduc through to the shallow Horseshoe Canyon/Scollard Formations. He has gained valuable experience in his career with Dome, Amoco, and Petrostar Petroleum, as well as Crestar Energy.

Title: Program Chair, Chemistry
Description:
Hi Warren - following up on your note below.  Thank you again for passing our name along to your contact.  Also, we wish you the best in establishing a science degree at RDC.  Per our discussion, we prefer to staff our labs with people who are comfortable and interested in living in smaller centers - away from the large cities.  Therefore, if we can tap into RDC students who share a common interest then we would be happy to find placements for them.

Please keep us posted on your developments.

Cheers :)

Chris



Warren Elgersma wrote:
> Hi Chris,
>
> I directed him to your website, so I guess if he is interested, he will contact you.  I will be seeing him tomorrow, so I'll mention this to him.
>
> It is unfortunate and frustrating that we still don't have an analytical chemistry course here.  We are hopeful that as our student numbers increase, we will be able to push for it again.  It looks like a slowdown in the economy might actually help us here. 
>
> A number of chemistry instructors in particular (including myself) really want to see this happen in the next couple of years.  We are also exploring the opportunity to offer a science degree at RDC in collaboration with another institution.  This would still take a number of years, but we are hopeful that in three or four years from now we will have some sort of degree program in science.  That would definitely help meet your challenge.

Title: Water Quality Specialist
Description:
Daniel Andrews, Ph.D., is a Water Quality Specialist with 19 years of experience. He has extensive experience in the oil sands, pulp and paper and mining industries where he served as principal investigator in numerous environmental effects monitoring and environmental impact studies. His principal areas of expertise include:

    * Water and sediment quality
    * Lake acidification and sediment contamination
    * Sediment and water toxicity
    * Environmental effects monitoring
    * Environmental impact assessment
    * Delineation of effluent plume dispersion
    * Benthic surveys and multivariate analysis of benthic populations
    * Bioavailability and environmental fate of aquatic contaminants
    * Analytical quality control

Title: CEO
Description:
Ms. Carin combines a background in technical design and commercialization, science and business with over 24 years experience in management and innovation.  Ms. Carin is the Chair of our Board and Chief Executive Officer, having held those positions since she founded EarthRenew in December 1999 and was our Chief Financial Officer from December 1999 to September 2007.  Ms. Carin is the primary inventor and continues to be the main developer of our technologies.  With her business development expertise, she leads the EarthRenew team in all aspects of product, process and equipment technology developments, commercialization, diversification, and adaption. 

In addition, Ms. Carin provides direction in corporate and financial strategies, providing an innovative work environment for a creative and talented team.  From 1993 to 1999, prior to founding EarthRenew, Ms. Carin was a consultant providing financial, business development and management services for a number of firms in British Columbia and Alberta including food and agriculture, livestock, manufacturing, hospitality and air transport.  Services included strategic planning, corporate restructuring, technology commercialization, financing, mergers and acquisitions.  From 1988 to 1992, Ms. Carin founded and headed a full service architectural and engineering firm in the Vancouver area providing services to governments and private sector clients throughout British Columbia, Canada.  Special projects included engineering designs for hospitals for hazardous and recycling waste management programs.  From 1981 to 1985, she was founder and President of a computer graphics firm in North Vancouver, providing innovative computer graphics services and established remote timeshare CADCAM services for engineering and architectural design firms in the Vancouver area.  Ms. Carin served for seven years as a board member and four years as Vice Chair with the Emily Carr University of Art + Design in Vancouver, British Columbia.  Ms. Carin holds a Master of Business Administration (Honors) degree in International Business from Asia Pacific International Institute (New Zealand), and a Bachelor of Fine Arts (Honors) degree from the University of British Columbia.

Title: COO
Description: Dr. Fedkenheuer has over 30 years experience in management in soil and environmental sciences.  Dr. Fedkenheuer has been our President since July 2004 and our Chief Operating Officer since September 2004.  He has been a director of EarthRenew since May 2000.  Over this period Dr. Fedkenheuer managed and contributed to our intellectual property development in both technology and product refinements.  His expertise extends to strategic planning, host development, permitting and regulatory affairs as well as leading the development of marketing and sales and product R&D strategies.  From 1990 to 1999, Dr. Fedkenheuer was a Senior Environmental Scientist and from 1982 to 1989 he was a Senior Environmental Specialist at TransCanada Pipelines, Ltd. (formerly NOVA Corporation) in Calgary, Alberta, Canada.  From 1980 to 1982 Dr. Fedkenheuer was Head, Land Reclamation, Environmental and Social Affairs with Canstar Oil Sands Ltd., Calgary, Alberta and from 1976 to 1980, a Reclamation Research Scientist with Syncrude Canada Ltd. Edmonton, Alberta.  Dr. Fedkenheuer co-founded ALCLA Native Plant Restoration Inc. in 1992.  He also founded the Canadian Native Plant Centre, a not-for-profit company with which he presently acts as President and Chairman.  Dr. Fedkenheuer has served as an Assistant Professor at Lakehead University, Ontario and as an active guest lecturer at the University of Alberta and Montana State University.  He currently serves as an Adjunct Associate Professor in the Faculty of Environmental Design at the University of Calgary.  Dr. Fedkenheuer holds a Ph.D. in Forest Ecology from the University of Minnesota as well as a Master of Science degree in Forest Soils and a Bachelor of Science degree in Agriculture from the University of Wisconsin.

Seneca Plant 
As part of optimising Orica?s North American operations it has been decided to close the Seneca Ammonium Nitrate (AN) plant.
Orica will continue to supply customer requirements for ammonium nitrate from its world scale AN facility in Alberta, Canada; from long term purchase and toll arrangements; and from its joint venture Ammonium Nitrate company, Geneva Nitrogen Inc. in Utah.


Estimated closure costs of A$9 million (post tax) and site remediation costs of A$22 million (post tax), after deducting estimated future sale proceeds, will be recognised as individually significant items in Orica?s financial statements for the year ending 30 September 2006. Once remediation is complete the site will be sold.
